[section {Simple Unmanaged Data}]

[section {Simple Unmanaged Data Types}]
    [subsection {int8}]
        In the tcl api library [const int8] values are represented as 
        regular tcl integers

    [subsection {int16}]
        In the tcl api library [const int16] values are represented as 
        regular tcl integers

    [subsection {int32}]
        In the tcl api library [const int32] values are represented as 
        regular tcl integers
    [subsection {int64}]
        In the tcl api library [const int64] values are represented as 
        regular tcl integers. This requires that Tcl 8.4 or greater
        be used with the Aptixia Tcl Client Library.

    [subsection {string}]
        [const string] values are represented using normal tcl strings

    [subsection {octets}]
        In the tcl api library normal tcl strings are used as
        [const octets] data elements. Tcl strings can
        contain arbitrary binary (nonascii) characters such as '\0'
        the tcl [const binary] command can be used to aid in creating
        binary [const octets] blobs

[section {Unmanaged Complex Data Types}]
    [subsection "Simple Lists"]

    [subsection "Node Lists"]

    [subsection "Polymorphic Node Lists"]
    Node Lists can be polymorphic. When these items in polymorphic node lists
    are retrieved via accessors like 'Get' they are retrieved as
    their characterized type, not as their generic base type.

    [example_begin]
    set pluginObject [lb]$portGroupObject stack childrenList Get 0[rb]
    puts stderr [lb]$pluginObject info type[rb]
    [example_end]

    [subsection "Enums"]
    Enums are implemented as classes. Usually you want to use them like
    like constants.  To allow for, this Each enum class has a set of 
    class constants for each possible value enumeration. Example:

    [example_begin]
    $myTestObject _Validate \
        $::AptixiaClient::XProtocolObject::ValidateMode::kDefaultValidation
    [example_end]


